# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agricultural-pollution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:agricultural-pollution/abiotic] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitrogen oxides (NOx) in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by US regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of carbonate rocks, such as limestone and marble.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China (the Minnan Golden Triangle) and Taiwan.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur dioxide pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] FGD gypsum is used in construction materials (e.g. concrete), and instead of natural gypsum it can be added to agricultural soils as a source of high-quality sulfur and calcium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles, but measures are required to further reduce road transport emissions, more especially in Diesel vehicles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Acid rain is now as severe a threat to the developing world, especially India and China, as it was earlier to some of the developed countries.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The purpose was to combat long-range transboundary air pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulphur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the Convention.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by emissions of particulate matter and sulphur dropping by 30-80% since 1990 in Europe and by 30-40% in North America.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of atmospheric pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Activity of the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Philippines, South Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emission allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emission allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acid-rain] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The actinide series is a group of chemical elements with atomic numbers ranging from 89 to 102, including notable elements such as uranium and plutonium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The nuclides (or isotopes) thorium-232, uranium-235, and uranium-238 occur primordially, while trace quantities of actinium, protactinium, neptunium, and plutonium exist as a result of radioactive decay and, in the case of neptunium and plutonium, neutron capture of uranium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] These elements have much shorter half-lives than the naturally occurring thorium and uranium, and thus are far more radioactive.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Elements with atomic numbers greater than 94 do not exist naturally on Earth, and must be produced in a nuclear reactor.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] However, certain isotopes of elements up to californium (atomic number 98) still have practical applications which take advantage of their radioactive properties.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] While all actinides are radioactive, actinides and their compounds comprise a significant portion of the Earth's crust.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] There is enough thorium and uranium to be commercially mined, with thorium having a concentration in the Earth's crust about four times that of uranium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The global production of uranium in 2021 was over six million tons, with Australia having been the leading supplier.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium is extracted as a byproduct of titanium, zirconium, tin, and rare earths from monazite, from which thorium is often a waste product.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Despite its greater abundance in the Earth's crust, the low demand for thorium in comparison to other metals extracted alongside thorium has led to a global surplus.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The primary hazard associated with actinides is their radioactivity, though they may also cause heavy metal poisoning if absorbed into the bloodstream.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Generally, ingested insoluble actinide compounds, such as uranium dioxide and mixed oxide (MOX) fuel, will pass through the digestive tract with little effect since they have long half-lives, and cannot dissolve and be absorbed into the bloodstream.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Inhaled actinide compounds, however, will be more damaging as they remain in the lungs and irradiate lung tissue.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Actinium can be found naturally in traces in uranium ore as 227Ac, which is an alpha and beta emitter with a half-life of 21.773 years.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Uranium ore contains about 0.2 mg of actinium per ton of uranium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is more commonly made in milligram amounts by neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Natural actinium almost exclusively consists of one isotope, 227Ac, with only minute traces of other shorter-lived isotopes (225Ac and 228Ac) occurring in other decay chains.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium is found at low levels in most rocks and soils, where it is about three times more abundant than uranium and about as abundant as lead.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] On average, soil commonly contains around 6 parts per million (ppm) thorium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium occurs in several minerals; the most common is the rare earth-thorium-phosphate mineral monazite, which contains up to 12% thorium oxide, of which several countries have substantial deposits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] 232Th decays very slowly, with its half-life being 14.0 billion years, about three times the age of the Earth.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Other isotopes of thorium occur in the thorium and uranium decay chains.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] These are shorter-lived and hence much more radioactive than 232Th, though on a mass basis they are negligible.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium has been linked to liver cancer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] In the past, thoria (thorium dioxide) was used as a contrast agent for medical X-ray radiography, sold under the name Thorotrast.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] In India, a large amount of thorium ore can be found in the form of monazite in placer deposits of the Western and Eastern coastal dune sands, particularly in the Tamil Nadu coastal areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The residents of this area are exposed to a naturally occurring radiation dose ten times higher than the worldwide average.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Protactinium is one of the rarest and most expensive naturally occurring elements.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is found in the form of two isotopes, 231Pa and 234Pa, with the isotope 234Pa occurring in two different energy states.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Nearly all natural protactinium is 231Pa.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is an alpha emitter and is formed by the decay of uranium-235, whereas the beta-radiating 234Pa is produced as a result of uranium-238 decay.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Nearly all uranium-238 (99.8%) decays first to the shorter-lived 234mPa isomer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Protactinium occurs in uraninite (pitchblende) at concentrations of about 0.3–3 parts 231Pa per million parts (ppm) of ore.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Whereas the usual content is closer to 0.3 ppm(e.g. in Jáchymov, Czech Republic), some ores from the Democratic Republic of the Congo have about 3 ppm.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Protactinium is homogeneously dispersed in most natural materials and in water, but at much lower concentrations on the order of one part per trillion, corresponding to a radioactivity of 0.1 picocuries (pCi)/g.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] There is about 500 times more protactinium in sandy soil particles than in water, even when compared to water present in the same sample of soil.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Much higher ratios of 2,000 and above are measured in loam soils and clays, such as bentonite.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is more plentiful than antimony, beryllium, cadmium, gold, mercury, silver, or tungsten, and is about as abundant as arsenic or molybdenum.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Significant concentrations of uranium occur in some substances such as phosphate rock deposits, minerals such as lignite, and monazite sands in uranium-rich ores, where it is also commercially extracted from.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Seawater contains about 3.3 parts per billion of uranium by weight as uranium (VI), which forms soluble carbonate complexes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Extraction of uranium from seawater has been considered as a means of obtaining the element.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Because of the very low specific activity of uranium, the chemical effects of it upon living things can often outweigh the effects of its radioactivity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Additional uranium has been added to the environment in some locations from the nuclear fuel cycle and the use of depleted uranium in munitions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Neptunium can be found naturally in low concentrations in uranium ore, where atoms of uranium-238 capture neutrons and undergo transmutation reactions, resulting in neptunium-237 and neptunium-239.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Despite this, it is relatively mobile over the long term, and diffusion of 237Np in groundwater is a major issue in designing a deep geological repository for permanent storage of spent nuclear fuel.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] 237Np has a half-life of 2.144 million years and is therefore a long-term problem; its half-life is still much shorter than those of uranium-238, uranium-235, or uranium-236, and therefore 237Np has higher specific activity than those nuclides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is used only to make plutonium-238 when bombarded with neutrons in a lab.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium occurs naturally in low concentrations in uranium ore.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium-238 is a product of the double beta decay of uranium-238, and plutonium-239 is a decay product of neptunium-239, which occurs when 238U undergoes a transmutation reaction due to neutron capture.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium-240 and plutonium-244 can also be found in nature, of which the latter's half-life of 81.3 million years has had it be suggested as a primordial radionuclide, though early reports of its detection could not be confirmed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium has many applications, and through these applications, trace amounts of plutonium have been released into the environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium, like other actinides, readily forms a dioxide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] In the environment, this plutonyl readily complexes with carbonate as well as other oxygen moieties (OH−, NO2−, NO3−, and SO42−) to form charged complexes which can be readily mobile with low affinities to soil.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] PuO2 formed from neutralizing highly acidic nitric acid solutions tends to form polymeric PuO2 which is resistant to complexation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium also readily shifts valences between the +3, +4, +5 and +6 states.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is common for some fraction of plutonium in solution to exist in all of these states in equilibrium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Like neptunium, plutonium is known to bind to soil particles very strongly.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] While caesium has very different chemistry from the actinides, it is well known that both caesium and many actinides bind strongly to the minerals in soil.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It has been possible to use 134Cs-labeled soil to study the migration of Pu and Cs is soils.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It has been shown that colloidal transport processes control the migration of Cs (and thus will control the migration of Pu) in the soil at the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Americium often enters landfills from discarded smoke detectors.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The rules for the disposal of smoke detectors are very relaxed in most municipalities.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] For instance, in the UK it is permissible to dispose of a smoke detector containing americium by placing it in the trash with normal household waste, but each trashcan is limited to only contain one smoke detector.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The manufacture of products containing americium, as well as nuclear reactors and explosions, may also release americium into the environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] In 1999, a truck transporting 900 smoke detectors in France was reported to have caught fire; it is claimed that this led to a release of americium into the environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] In the U.S., the "Radioactive Boy Scout" David Hahn was able to buy thousands of smoke detectors at remainder prices and concentrate the americium from them.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] There have been cases of humans being exposed to americium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The worst case was that of Harold McCluskey, who was exposed to an extremely high dose of americium-241 after an accident involving a glove box.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] He was subsequently treated with chelation therapy.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] It is likely that the medical care which he was given saved his life; despite similar biodistribution and toxicity to plutonium, the two radioactive elements have different solution-state chemistries.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Americium is stable in the +3 oxidation state, while the +4 oxidation state of plutonium can form in the human body.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] The most common isotope americium-241 decays with a half-life of 432 years to neptunium-237.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] In the long term, the issues discussed above for neptunium apply.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Americium released into the environment tends to remain in soil and water at relatively shallow depths and may be taken up by animals and plants during growth; shellfish such as shrimp take up americium-241 in their shells, and parts of grain plants can become contaminated by exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Chaplin et al. reported advances in the diffusive gradients in thin films technique, which have provided a method to measure labile bioavailable americium in soils, as well as in freshwater and seawater.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Atmospheric curium compounds are poorly soluble in common solvents and mostly adhere to soil particles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Soil analysis revealed about 4,000 times higher concentration of curium in the sandy soil particles than in water present in the soil pores.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] An even higher ratio of about 18,000 was measured in loam soils.
[src:agricultural-pollution/actinides-in-the-environment] Californium is fairly insoluble in water, but it adheres well to ordinary soil, and concentrations of it in the soil can be 500 times higher than in the water surrounding the soil particles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS involves a total dose of greater than 0.7 Gy (70 rad), which generally occurs from a source outside the body, delivered within a few minutes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Sources of such radiation can occur accidentally or intentionally.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] They may involve nuclear reactors, cyclotrons, certain devices used in cancer therapy, nuclear weapons, or radiological weapons.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] It is generally divided into three types: bone marrow, gastrointestinal, and neurovascular syndrome, with bone marrow syndrome occurring at 0.7 to 10 Gy, and neurovascular syndrome occurring at doses that exceed 50 Gy.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The cells that are most affected are generally those that are rapidly dividing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] At high doses, this causes DNA damage that may be irreparable.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Diagnosis is based on a history of exposure and symptoms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Repeated complete blood counts (CBCs) can indicate the severity of exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Treatment of ARS is generally supportive care.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This may include blood transfusions, antibiotics, colony-stimulating factors, or stem cell transplant.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radioactive material remaining on the skin or in the stomach should be removed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] If radioiodine was inhaled or ingested, potassium iodide is recommended.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Complications such as leukemia and other cancers among those who survive are managed as usual.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Short-term outcomes depend on the dose exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] A single event can affect a large number of people.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The vast majority of cases involving ARS, alongside blast effects, were inflicted by the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, with post-attack deaths in the tens of thousands.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents sometimes cause ARS; the worst, the Chernobyl nuclear power plant disaster, caused 134 cases and 28 deaths.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS differs from chronic radiation syndrome, which occurs following prolonged exposures to relatively low doses of radiation, and from radiation-induced cancer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Classically, ARS is divided into three main presentations: hematopoietic, gastrointestinal, and neurovascular.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] These syndromes may be preceded by a prodrome.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The speed of symptom onset is related to radiation exposure, with greater doses resulting in a shorter delay in symptom onset.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] These presentations presume whole-body exposure, and many of them are markers that are invalid if the entire body has not been exposed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Each syndrome requires that the tissue showing the syndrome itself be exposed (for instance, gastrointestinal syndrome is not seen if the stomach and intestines are not exposed to radiation).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This syndrome often follows absorbed doses of 6–30 grays (600–3,000 rad).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The signs and symptoms of this form of radiation injury include nausea, vomiting, loss of appetite, and abdominal pain.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Vomiting in this time-frame (1-2h post-exposure) is a marker for whole-body exposures that are in the fatal range above 4 grays (400 rad).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Without exotic treatment such as bone marrow transplant, death with this dose is common, due generally more to infection than gastrointestinal dysfunction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This syndrome typically occurs at absorbed doses greater than 30 grays (3,000 rad), though it may occur at doses as low as 10 grays (1,000 rad).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] It presents with neurological symptoms such as dizziness, headache, or decreased level of consciousness, occurring within minutes to a few hours, with an absence of vomiting, and is almost always fatal, even with aggressive intensive care.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Early symptoms of ARS typically include nausea, vomiting, headaches, fatigue, fever, and a short period of skin reddening.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] These symptoms may occur at radiation doses as low as 0.35 grays (35 rad).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] These symptoms are common to many illnesses, and may not, by themselves, indicate acute radiation sickness.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] A person who was less than 1 mile (1.6 km) from the atomic bomb *Little Boy*'s hypocenter at Hiroshima, Japan, was found to have absorbed about 9.46 grays (Gy) of ionizing radiation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The doses at the hypocenters of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic bombings were 240 and 290 Gy, respectively.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Cutaneous radiation syndrome (CRS) refers to the skin symptoms of radiation exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Within a few hours after irradiation, a transient and inconsistent redness (associated with itching) can occur.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Then, a latent phase may occur and last from a few days up to several weeks, when intense reddening, blistering, and ulceration of the irradiated site is visible.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] In most cases, healing occurs by regenerative means; however, very large skin doses can cause permanent hair loss, damaged sebaceous and sweat glands, atrophy, fibrosis (mostly keloids), decreased or increased skin pigmentation, and ulceration or necrosis of the exposed tissue.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] As seen at Chernobyl, when skin is irradiated with high energy beta particles, moist desquamation (peeling of skin) and similar early effects can heal, only to be followed by the collapse of the dermal vascular system after two months, resulting in the loss of the full thickness of the exposed skin.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Another example of skin loss caused by high-level exposure of radiation is during the 1999 Tokaimura nuclear accident, where technician Hisashi Ouchi had lost a majority of his skin due to the high amounts of radiation he absorbed during the irradiation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This effect had been demonstrated previously with pig skin using high energy beta sources at the Churchill Hospital Research Institute, in Oxford.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS is caused by exposure to a large dose of ionizing radiation (> ≈ 0.1 Gy) over a short period of time (> ≈ 0.1 Gy/h).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Alpha and beta radiation have low penetrating power and are unlikely to affect vital internal organs from outside the body.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Any type of ionizing radiation can cause burns, but alpha and beta radiation can only do so if radioactive contamination or nuclear fallout is deposited on the individual's skin or clothing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Gamma and neutron radiation can travel much greater distances and penetrate the body easily, so whole-body irradiation generally causes ARS before skin effects are evident.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Local gamma irradiation can cause skin effects without any sickness.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] In the early twentieth century, radiographers would commonly calibrate their machines by irradiating their own hands and measuring the time to onset of erythema.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Accidental exposure may be the result of a criticality or radiotherapy accident.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There have been numerous criticality accidents dating back to atomic testing during World War II, while computer-controlled radiation therapy machines such as Therac-25 played a major part in radiotherapy accidents.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The latter of the two is caused by the failure of equipment software used to monitor the radiational dose given.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Human error has played a large part in accidental exposure incidents, including some of the criticality accidents, and larger scale events such as the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Other events have to do with orphan sources, in which radioactive material is unknowingly kept, sold, or stolen.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The Goiânia accident is an example, where a forgotten radioactive source was taken from a hospital, resulting in the deaths of 4 people from ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Theft and attempted theft of radioactive material by clueless thieves has also led to lethal exposure in at least one incident.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Exposure may also come from routine spaceflight and solar flares, which result in radiation effects on earth in the form of solar storms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] During spaceflight, astronauts are exposed to both galactic cosmic radiation (GCR) and solar particle event (SPE) radiation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The exposure particularly occurs during flights beyond low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Evidence indicates past SPE radiation levels that would have been lethal for unprotected astronauts.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] GCR levels that might lead to acute radiation poisoning are less well understood.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The latter cause is rarer, with an event possibly occurring during the solar storm of 1859.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Intentional exposure is controversial as it involves the use of nuclear weapons, human experiments, or is given to a victim in an act of murder.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The intentional atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki resulted in tens of thousands of casualties; the survivors of these bombings are known today as *hibakusha*.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Nuclear weapons emit large amounts of thermal radiation as visible, infrared, and ultraviolet light, to which the atmosphere is largely transparent.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This event is also known as "flash", where radiant heat and light are bombarded into any given victim's exposed skin, causing radiation burns.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Death is highly likely, and radiation poisoning is almost certain if one is caught in the open with no terrain or building masking-effects within a radius of 0–3 km from a 1 megaton airburst.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The 50% chance of death from the blast extends out to ≈ 8 km from a 1 megaton atmospheric explosion.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Scientific testing on humans within the United States occurred extensively throughout the atomic age.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Experiments took place on a range of subjects including, but not limited to; the disabled, children, soldiers, and incarcerated persons, with the level of understanding and consent given by subjects varying from complete to none.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Since 1997 there have been requirements for patients to give informed consent, and to be notified if experiments were classified.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The Soviet nuclear program also included medical study of exposed citizens living near Semipalatinsk Test Site, withholding information about nuclear testing or health risks.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The program also involved severe radiation exposures to workers of the Mayak facility, especially the early work of forced laborers on the A-1 nuclear reactor.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Criminal activity has involved murder and attempted murder carried out through abrupt victim contact with a radioactive substance such as polonium or plutonium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The death of Alexander Litvinenko is widely believed to be assassination via polonium poisoning and on the order of the Russian FSB, and polonium is also suspected as the cause of death for Yasser Arafat, Yuri Shchekochikhin, Lecha Islamov and Roman Tsepov.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The most commonly used predictor of ARS is the whole-body absorbed dose.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Several related quantities, such as the equivalent dose, effective dose, and committed dose, are used to gauge long-term stochastic biological effects such as cancer incidence, but they are not designed to evaluate ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] To help avoid confusion between these quantities, absorbed dose is measured in units of grays (in SI, unit symbol *Gy*) or rad (in CGS), while the others are measured in sieverts (in SI, unit symbol *Sv*) or rem (in CGS).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] In most of the acute exposure scenarios that lead to radiation sickness, the bulk of the radiation is external whole-body gamma, in which case the absorbed, equivalent, and effective doses are all equal.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There are exceptions, such as the Therac-25 accidents and the 1958 Cecil Kelley criticality accident, where the absorbed doses in Gy or rad are the only useful quantities, because of the targeted nature of the exposure to the body.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiotherapy treatments are typically prescribed in terms of the local absorbed dose, which might be 60 Gy or higher.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The dose is fractionated to about 2 Gy per day for *curative* treatment, which allows normal tissues to undergo repair, allowing them to tolerate a higher dose than would otherwise be expected.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The dose to the targeted tissue mass must be averaged over the entire body mass, most of which receives negligible radiation, to arrive at a whole-body absorbed dose that can be compared to the table above.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Exposure to high doses of radiation causes DNA damage, later creating serious and even lethal chromosomal aberrations if left unrepaired.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Ionizing radiation can produce reactive oxygen species, and does directly damage cells by causing localized ionization events.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The former is very damaging to DNA, while the latter events create clusters of DNA damage.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This damage includes loss of nucleobases and breakage of the sugar-phosphate backbone that binds to the nucleobases.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The DNA organization at the level of histones, nucleosomes, and chromatin also affects its susceptibility to radiation damage.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Clustered damage, defined as at least two lesions within a helical turn, is especially harmful.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] While DNA damage happens frequently and naturally in the cell from endogenous sources, clustered damage is a unique effect of radiation exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Clustered damage takes longer to repair than isolated breakages, and is less likely to be repaired at all.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Larger radiation doses are more prone to cause tighter clustering of damage, and closely localized damage is increasingly less likely to be repaired.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Somatic mutations cannot be passed down from parent to offspring, but these mutations can propagate in cell lines within an organism.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiation damage can also cause chromosome and chromatid aberrations, and their effects depend on in which stage of the mitotic cycle the cell is when the irradiation occurs.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] If the cell is in interphase, while it is still a single strand of chromatin, the damage will be replicated during the S1 phase of the cell cycle, and there will be a break on both chromosome arms; the damage then will be apparent in both daughter cells.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] If the irradiation occurs after replication, only one arm will bear the damage; this damage will be apparent in only one daughter cell.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] A damaged chromosome may cyclize, binding to another chromosome, or to itself.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Diagnosis is typically made based on a history of significant radiation exposure and suitable clinical findings.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] An absolute lymphocyte count can give a rough estimate of radiation exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Time from exposure to vomiting can also give estimates of exposure levels if they are less than 10 Gy (1000 rad).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] A guiding principle of radiation safety is *as low as reasonably achievable* (ALARA).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This means try to avoid exposure as much as possible and includes the three components of time, distance, and shielding.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The longer that humans are subjected to radiation the larger the dose will be.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The advice in the nuclear war manual entitled *Nuclear War Survival Skills* published by Cresson Kearny in the U.S. was that if one needed to leave the shelter then this should be done as rapidly as possible to minimize exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] In chapter 12, he states that "[q]uickly putting or dumping wastes outside is not hazardous once fallout is no longer being deposited.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] For example, assume the shelter is in an area of heavy fallout and the dose rate outside is 400 roentgen (R) per hour, enough to give a potentially fatal dose in about an hour to a person exposed in the open.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] If a person needs to be exposed for only 10 seconds to dump a bucket, in this 1/360 of an hour he will receive a dose of only about 1 R.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Under war conditions, an additional 1-R dose is of little concern." In peacetime, radiation workers are taught to work as quickly as possible when performing a task that exposes them to radiation, such as for instance during recovery of a radioactive source.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Usually, matter attenuates radiation, so placing any mass (for instance, lead, dirt, sandbags, vehicles, water, even air) between humans and the source will reduce the radiation dose.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This is not always the case, however; care should be taken when constructing shielding for a specific purpose.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] For example, although high atomic number materials are very effective in shielding photons, using them to shield beta particles may cause higher radiation exposure due to the production of bremsstrahlung x-rays, and hence low atomic number materials are recommended.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Also, using material with a high neutron activation cross section to shield neutrons will result in the shielding material itself becoming radioactive and hence more dangerous than if it were not present.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There are many types of shielding strategies that can be used to reduce the effects of radiation exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Internal contamination protective equipment such as respirators are used to prevent internal deposition as a result of inhalation and ingestion of radioactive material.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Dermal protective equipment, which protects against external contamination, provides shielding to prevent radioactive material from being deposited on external structures.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] While these protective measures do provide a barrier from radioactive material deposition, they do not shield from externally penetrating gamma radiation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This leaves anyone exposed to penetrating gamma rays at high risk of ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Naturally, shielding the entire body from high energy gamma radiation is optimal, but the required mass to provide adequate attenuation makes functional movement nearly impossible.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] In the event of a radiation catastrophe, medical and security personnel need mobile protection equipment in order to safely assist in containment, evacuation, and many other necessary public safety objectives.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Research has been done exploring the feasibility of partial body shielding, a radiation protection strategy that provides adequate attenuation to only the most radio-sensitive organs and tissues inside the body.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Irreversible stem cell damage in the bone marrow is the first life-threatening effect of intense radiation exposure and therefore one of the most important bodily elements to protect.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Due to the regenerative property of hematopoietic stem cells, it is only necessary to protect enough bone marrow to repopulate the exposed areas of the body with the shielded supply.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This concept allows for the development of lightweight mobile radiation protection equipment, which provides adequate protection, deferring the onset of ARS to much higher exposure doses.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] One example of such equipment is the 360 Gamma, a radiation protection belt that applies selective shielding to protect the bone marrow stored in the pelvic area as well as other radio sensitive organs in the abdominal region without hindering functional mobility.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Where radioactive contamination is present, an elastomeric respirator, dust mask, or good hygiene practices may offer protection, depending on the nature of the contaminant.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Potassium iodide (KI) tablets can reduce the risk of cancer in some situations due to slower uptake of ambient radioiodine.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Although this does not protect any organ other than the thyroid gland, their effectiveness is still highly dependent on the time of ingestion, which would protect the gland for the duration of a twenty-four-hour period.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] They do not prevent ARS as they provide no shielding from other environmental radionuclides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] If an intentional dose is broken up into a number of smaller doses, with time allowed for recovery between irradiations, the same total dose causes less cell death.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Even without interruptions, a reduction in dose rate below 0.1 Gy/h also tends to reduce cell death.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] This technique is routinely used in radiotherapy.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The human body contains many types of cells and a human can be killed by the loss of a single type of cells in a vital organ.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] For many short term radiation deaths (3–30 days), the loss of two important types of cells that are constantly being regenerated causes death.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The loss of cells forming blood cells (bone marrow) and the cells in the digestive system (microvilli, which form part of the wall of the intestines) is fatal.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Treatment usually involves supportive care with possible symptomatic measures employed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The former involves the possible use of antibiotics, blood products, colony stimulating factors, and stem cell transplant.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There is a direct relationship between the degree of the neutropenia that emerges after exposure to radiation and the increased risk of developing infection.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Since there are no controlled studies of therapeutic intervention in humans, most of the current recommendations are based on animal research.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The treatment of established or suspected infection following exposure to radiation (characterized by neutropenia and fever) is similar to the one used for other febrile neutropenic patients.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] However, important differences between the two conditions exist.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Individuals that develop neutropenia after exposure to radiation are also susceptible to irradiation damage in other tissues, such as the gastrointestinal tract, lungs and central nervous system.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] These patients may require therapeutic interventions not needed in other types of neutropenic patients.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The response of irradiated animals to antimicrobial therapy can be unpredictable, as was evident in experimental studies where metronidazole and pefloxacin therapies were detrimental.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Antimicrobials that reduce the number of the strict anaerobic component of the gut flora (for instance, metronidazole) generally should not be given because they may enhance systemic infection by aerobic or facultative bacteria, thus facilitating mortality after irradiation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] An empirical regimen of antimicrobials should be chosen based on the pattern of bacterial susceptibility and nosocomial infections in the affected area and medical center and the degree of neutropenia.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Broad-spectrum empirical therapy (see below for choices) with high doses of one or more antibiotics should be initiated at the onset of fever.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] These antimicrobials should be directed at the eradication of Gram-negative aerobic bacilli (that is, Enterobacteriaceae, *Pseudomonas*), which account for more than three quarters of the isolates causing sepsis.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Because aerobic and facultative Gram-positive bacteria (mostly alpha-hemolytic streptococci) cause sepsis in about a quarter of the victims, coverage for these organisms may also be needed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] A standardized management plan for people with neutropenia and fever should be devised.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The prognosis for ARS is dependent on the exposure dose, with anything above 8 Gy being almost always lethal, even with medical care.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiation burns from lower-level exposures usually manifest after 2 months, while reactions from the burns occur months to years after radiation treatment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Complications from ARS include an increased risk of developing radiation-induced cancer later in life.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] According to the controversial but commonly applied linear no-threshold model, any exposure to ionizing radiation, even at doses too low to produce any symptoms of radiation sickness, can induce cancer due to cellular and genetic damage.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The probability of developing cancer is a linear function with respect to the effective radiation dose.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiation cancer may occur after ionizing radiation exposure following a latent period averaging 20 to 40 years.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Acute effects of ionizing radiation were first observed when Wilhelm Röntgen intentionally subjected his fingers to X-rays in 1895.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] He published his observations concerning the burns that developed that eventually healed, and misattributed them to ozone.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Röntgen believed the free radical produced in air by X-rays from the ozone was the cause, but other free radicals produced within the body are now understood to be more important.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] David Walsh first established the symptoms of radiation sickness in 1897.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Ingestion of radioactive materials caused many radiation-induced cancers in the 1930s, but no one was exposed to high enough doses at high enough rates to bring on ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki resulted in high acute doses of radiation to a large number of Japanese people, allowing for greater insight into its symptoms and dangers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Red Cross Hospital Surgeon Terufumi Sasaki led intensive research into the syndrome in the weeks and months following the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Sasaki and his team were able to monitor the effects of radiation in patients of varying proximities to the blast itself, leading to the establishment of three recorded stages of the syndrome.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Within 25–30 days of the explosion, Sasaki noticed a sharp drop in white blood cell count and established this drop, along with symptoms of fever, as prognostic standards for ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Actress Midori Naka, who was present during the atomic bombing of Hiroshima, was the first incident of radiation poisoning to be extensively studied.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Her death on 24 August 1945 was the first death ever to be officially certified as a result of ARS (or "Atomic bomb disease").
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There are two major databases that track radiation accidents: The American ORISE REAC/TS and the European IRSN ACCIRAD.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] REAC/TS shows 417 accidents occurring between 1944 and 2000, causing about 3000 cases of ARS, of which 127 were fatal.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] ACCIRAD lists 580 accidents with 180 ARS fatalities for an almost identical period.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The two deliberate bombings are not included in either database, nor are any possible radiation-induced cancers from low doses.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The detailed accounting is difficult because of confounding factors.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS may be accompanied by conventional injuries such as steam burns, or may occur in someone with a pre-existing condition undergoing radiotherapy.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There may be multiple causes for death, and the contribution from radiation may be unclear.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Some documents may incorrectly refer to radiation-induced cancers as radiation poisoning, or may count all overexposed individuals as survivors without mentioning if they had any symptoms of ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The following table includes only individuals known to have symptoms of ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Excluded are cases of chronic radiation syndrome, such as the case of Albert Stevens.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Chronic radiation syndrome is characterized by an exposure of lower doses of radiation, over a longer duration, than with ARS.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The table also excludes cases where an individual was exposed to so much radiation that death occurred before medical assistance or dose estimations could be made, such as an attempted cobalt-60 thief who reportedly died 30 minutes after exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] The result column represents the time from exposure to the time of death.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] As ARS is measured by a whole-body absorbed dose, the exposure column only includes units of gray (Gy).
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] Thousands of scientific experiments have been performed to study ARS in animals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/acute-radiation-syndrome] There is a simple guide for predicting survival and death in mammals, including humans, following the acute effects of inhaling radioactive particles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Advertising mail includes advertising circulars, plastic mailers, coupon envelopes (Money Mailer, Valpak), catalogs, CDs, "pre-approved" credit card applications, and other commercial merchandising materials delivered to homes and businesses.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] It may be addressed to pre-selected individuals, or unaddressed and delivered on a neighbourhood-by-neighbourhood basis.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] North Carolina state historians say Lunsford Richardson "is widely to considered to have invented ‘junk mail.’" In the process of expanding the market for his new products made by the Vicks company of Greensboro, North Carolina.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Postal Service began allowing mail to be sent to rural addresses without including the name of the addressee.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Vicks sent out millions of samples of Vicks VapoRub.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Postal systems offer lower rates for buyers of bulk mail permits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In order to qualify for these rates, marketers must format and sort the mail in specific ways – which reduces the handling required by the postal service.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Income from advertising mail represents a significant and growing portion of some postal services' budgets, and it is a service actively marketed by them.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In the United States, ad mail dollars decreased from $96.6 billion in 2004, to $80.9 billion in 2013.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] A study by Boston Consulting Group predicts that overall share of ad-spend in the US will increase from 11% in to 12% by 2020.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In Canada, addressed and unaddressed advertising mail accounted for 20% of Canada Post's revenue in 2005, and the share is increasing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Postal services employ the terms *advertising mail*, *admail*, and *direct mail*, while avoiding and objecting to the pejorative term *junk mail*.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The United States Postal Service offers a direct mail service known as Every Door Direct Mail, that provides resources allowing businesses to target, design, print and mail to specific households without needing to know the addresses.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In many developed countries, advertising mail represents a significant and growing amount of the total volume of mail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In the United States, "Standard mail: advertising" comprised 29% of all mail in 1980 and 43% in 2003.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Direct mail is a common form of direct marketing, and may be employed by for-profit businesses, charities and other non-profits, political campaigns, and other organizations.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Direct mail encompasses a wide variety of marketing materials, including brochures, catalogs, postcards, newsletters and sales letters.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In 2015 more than 150 million direct mail promotions were sent out with a reported 42% of respondents scanning or reading the mail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Scammers also use direct mail in the form of auto warranty and home warranty scams.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Copywriters write the words, also known as copy, for direct mail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] These copywriters are known inside the trade as direct response copywriters.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Direct response copy follows a proven format based on testing results.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Graphic designers who specialize in direct marketing also play a key role in the success of direct mail programs.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Many direct mail marketers will mail different version of copy (A/B testing) to test the effectiveness of different appeals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The winning mail package will be known as the control and the direct mail company will continue to mail the control until a different package produces improved results, usually measured by metrics such as revenue and conversion rate.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Some campaigns incorporate tactile embellishments—such as foil stamping, embossing, specialty UV coatings, metallic finishes, and soft-touch laminates—to attract attention and encourage interaction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Advertisers often refine direct mail practices into targeted mailing in which mail is sent following database analysis to select recipients considered most likely to respond positively.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] This reduces costs for mailers by narrowing the mailing universe to only the most likely audience.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] For example, a person who has demonstrated an interest in golf may receive direct mail for golf-related products or perhaps for goods and services that are appropriate for golfers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] This use of database analysis is a type of database marketing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Alternatively, unaddressed direct mail may be sent on a neighbourhood-by-neighbourhood basis.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Whether at the individual or neighbourhood level, direct mail marketing allows recipients to be targeted, attempting to match the demographic profile of the recipients to one most closely matching that of likely customers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Individually targeted direct mail may be tailored based on previous transactions and gathered data.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] For example, all male recipients of an offer may receive a personalized package with a man's picture on the cover while all female recipients receive a picture of a woman.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Often advertisers will include a Johnson Box in letters.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] These are aimed at drawing the targeted consumers into reading further in the letter.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] To the non-professional, direct mail may seem wasteful, yet the medium can be one of the most cost-effective.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Database targeting combined with an effective pricing, creative and list strategy can reduce waste and maximize profitable results for the mailer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Testing is accomplished in a variety of ways including A/B split testing of new mailings versus a control and testing lists through "Nth" name selects.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Political campaigns make frequent use of direct mail, both to gain votes from the electorate as a whole, and to target certain groups of voters thought to be open to a candidate's message and to appeal for campaign funds.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Certain organizations and individuals have become known for their prowess in direct mail, including in the US, the Free Congress Foundation in the 1970s, Response Dynamics, Inc. in the 1980s, the National Congressional Club, and Richard Viguerie.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] With the advent of the Internet in political campaigns, direct mail became just one of many campaign management tools, but still played a significant role.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Nonprofit companies use direct mail marketing as a consistent form of advertising.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In its modern form, direct mail fundraising appeared in the United States after World War II when nationwide charities such as the National Easter Seal Society sought ways to broaden their fundraising base.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] It was only with the advent in the 1960s of the ZIP code and, later, the computer that direct mail fundraising began to gain wide use.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Before the ZIP code, it was difficult to target appropriate recipients of direct mail fundraising appeals, and before the computer, compiling and maintaining lists of supporters was tedious and costly.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] During the 1970s, when computers became increasingly affordable, the use of direct mail fundraising spread widely.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] It quickly became the means by which most Americans learned about and first provided financial support for their charities of choice.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The explosive growth of the nonprofit sector in the United States—quadrupling in the 1980s and doubling again in the 1990s and early 2000s—led to a massive expansion in the use of direct mail to build and sustain large, nationwide donor and membership lists.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In recent years, electronic communication media has been used more commonly among nonprofits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Online, email, and social media campaigns, collectively referred to as digital fundraising, have been used in coordination with direct mail fundraising.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Nonprofits supplement direct mail campaigns with email blasts and social media posts, using similar messaging and visuals to tie the various communications together.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] However, digital fundraising has not grown fast enough to replace direct mail for most nonprofits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In 2012, digital fundraising accounted for 7 percent of charitable donations in the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] This form of marketing is increasingly used by charitable groups in the UK.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In 2013, £239 million was spent by British charities on direct mail advertising campaigns.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Direct mail marketing is under scrutiny by many of its former and current advocates.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The arguments against using direct mail marketing include possible impact on the environment and changing attitudes among consumers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In the United States, the common practice of address standardization can defeat the purpose of advertising mail by stripping away local identity, thus leaving many recipients alienated.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] It is also argued that direct mail is not cost-efficient.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] It has been suggested that social media will eventually replace direct mail as the preferred method for marketing communications.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Those who believe direct mail marketing has a future cite its strong growth in 2011.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] It has been reported that large publishers like the Tribune Company and RR Donnelley have growing direct mail divisions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Nonprofit organizations continue to use direct mail at a subsidized USPS rate.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] When targeted to other businesses rather than individuals, direct mail is known as a business-to-business mailing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Traditionally, this worked in one of two ways: as a direct sale, therefore precluding the use of a salesperson or a retail store, or as a method of generating leads for a salesforce.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The former method was ideally used by products that were easy to sell, were familiar to the prospect and needed no demonstration.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The latter method was used for large-ticket items or for those that needed demonstration, for example.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] One method of direct mailing used in B2B is known as "bill-me." In this direct-mail marketing offer, the buyer is shipped the product prior to payment and is then sent an invoice later.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Several organizations offer opt-out services to people who wish to reduce or eliminate the amount of addressed advertising mail they receive.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In the UK, the Mailing Preference Service allows people to register with them for removal from posted as opposed to hand-delivered mail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] As of 2017 in the United States two organizations offering these services include Catalog Choice and DMAChoice.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] A similar organization by the name of 41pounds.org received customer complaints and then became defunct.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Another one by the name of Tonic Mailstopper (formerly GreenDimes) no longer appears to be in business either.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Several websites critical of junk mail have guides for people interested in reducing the amount of junk mail they get, such as the Center for a New American Dream.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In response to a US Supreme Court ruling (*Rowan v.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] 728 (1970)), the United States Postal Service enables an applicant to obtain a Prohibitory Order, which gives people the power to stop non-governmental organizations from sending them mail, and to demand such organizations remove the consumers’ information from their mailing lists.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In Canada, the highly publicized Red Dot Campaign offers advice on reducing unaddressed advertising mail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The campaign focuses on advertising the Canada Post policy to respect "No Junkmail" signs, noting that this policy is not promoted by Canada Post itself.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The name "red dot" refers to an internal marker used by Canada Post to indicate which households do not wish to receive unaddressed admail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The UK Royal Mail also offers an opt-out service, though unaddressed government mailings cannot be separated from advertisements, and those who opted out of the latter would stop receiving the former as well.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Several environmental groups express concern about the environmental impact generated by direct mail.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In the US, the Environmental Protection Agency estimates that 44% of junk mail is discarded without being opened or read, equalling four million tons of waste paper per year, with 32% recovered for recycling.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Further, the Ohio Office of Compliance Assistance and Pollution Prevention (OCAPP) estimates that 250,000 homes could be heated for a single day's junk mail (70,000,000,000,000/3 btus of energy or 28,870,000,000/21 kWh of energy).
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] In the UK, the Minister of State responsible for the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs estimated that "direct mail and promotions" accounted for between 500,000 and 600,000 tonnes of paper in 2002, with 13% being recycled.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The government and the Direct Marketing Association (UK) together agreed on recycling targets for the direct mail industry, including a goal of 55% by 2009, though the DMA's latest estimates are that the industry will fall well short of this mark.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Mike Berners-Lee estimates that receiving five letters per day plus two printed catalogs per week results in 480 kilograms (1,060 lb) CO2e per year.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] A *New York Times* article from 2009 states that in the United States 51.5 million metric tons of greenhouse gases are emitted each year from mail advertisements.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] The Environmental Protection Agency indicates that in 2009 total US greenhouse gas emissions were 6,700.10 million metric tons.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Recipients may conceive of advertising mail as a privacy problem, both because its generation requires extensive collection and use of information, and because receipt of mail can be an intrusion into the home.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Researchers at the University of California recently found that four out of five Americans favor a do-not-mail law, similar to the existing do-not-call telemarketing registry.
[src:agricultural-pollution/advertising-mail] Advertising mail has been criticized as a form of attention theft.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Agricultural aircraft are highly specialized, purpose-built aircraft.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Today's agricultural aircraft are often powered by turbine engines of up to 1,500 shp (1,100 kW) and can carry as much as 800 US gallons (3,000 L) of crop protection product.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Helicopters are sometimes used, and some aircraft serve double duty as water bombers in areas prone to wildfires.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The first known aerial application of agricultural materials was by John Chaytor, who in 1906 spread seed over a swamped valley floor in Wairoa, New Zealand, using a hot air balloon with mobile tethers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Aerial sowing of seed still continues to this day with cover crop applications and rice planting.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The first known use of a heavier-than-air machine to disperse products occurred on August 3, 1921.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Crop dusting was developed under the joint efforts of the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Army Signal Corps' research station at McCook Field in Dayton, Ohio.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Under the direction of McCook engineer Etienne Dormoy, a United States Army Air Service Curtiss JN4 Jenny piloted by John A.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Macready was modified at McCook Field to spread lead arsenate to kill catalpa sphinx caterpillars at a catalpa farm near Troy, Ohio in the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The first test was considered highly successful.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The first commercial cropdusting operations began in 1924 in Macon, Georgia by Huff-Daland Crop Dusting, which was co-founded by McCook Field test pilot Lt.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Use of insecticide and fungicide for crop dusting slowly spread in the Americas and, to a lesser extent, other nations in the 1930s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The name 'crop dusting' originated here, as actual dust was spread across the crops.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Today, aerial applicators use liquid crop protection products in very small doses.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Aerial topdressing is the aerial application of fertilisers over farmland using agricultural aircraft.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] It was developed in New Zealand in the 1940s and rapidly adopted elsewhere in the 1950s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] In 1951, Leland Snow designed the first aircraft specifically built for aerial application, the S-1.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] In 1957, The Grumman G-164 Ag-Cat was the first aircraft designed by a major company for agricultural aviation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Currently, the most common agricultural aircraft are the Air Tractor, Cessna Ag-wagon, Gippsland GA200, Grumman Ag Cat, PZL-106 KRUK, M-18 Dromader, PAC Fletcher, Piper PA-36 Pawnee Brave, Embraer EMB 202 Ipanema, and Rockwell Thrush Commander, but multi-purpose helicopters are also used.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Since the late 1990s, unmanned aerial vehicles have also been used for agricultural spraying.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] This phenomenon started in Japan and South Korea, where mountainous terrain and relatively small family-owned farms required lower-cost and higher-precision spraying.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] As of 2014, the use of UAV crop dusters, such as the Yamaha R-MAX, is being expanded to the United States for use in spraying at vineyards.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences keeps track of relevant research.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Historically, there has been concerns about the effects of aerial applications of pesticides and the chemicals' effects as they spread in the air.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] For example, the aerial application of mancozeb is likely a source of concern for pregnant women.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] Since the 1970s, multiple countries started to limit or ban the aerial application of pesticides, fertilizers, and other products out of environmental and public health concerns, in particular from spray drift.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) provides guideline documents and hosts webinars about best practices for aerial application.
[src:agricultural-pollution/aerial-application] In 2010, the United States Forest Service collected public comments to use within a Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIS), which was developed because the Montana Federal District Court ruled that aerial application of fire retardants during wildfires violated the Endangered Species Act.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange was produced in the United States beginning in the late 1940s and was used in industrial agriculture, and was also sprayed along railroads and power lines to control undergrowth in forests.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Nine chemical companies produced it, including Dow Chemical Company and Monsanto Company.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange exposure is linked to increased rates of birth defects, malignancies, cardiovascular diseases, and diabetes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The science on the causality between exposure and health problems remains incomplete.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. government has documented cases of leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma, and various kinds of cancer in exposed U.S. veterans, but not concluded a causal relationship or a plausible biological carcinogenic mechanism.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention identified an increase in the rate of birth defects of the children of exposed U.S. veterans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The impact of Agent Orange in Vietnam includes health and ecological effects.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The government of Vietnam defined victims of Agent Orange by looking at where they live, their family history, and if the health problems have been linked to Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. government has described these figures as unreliable.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange has also caused enormous environmental damage in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] This has been described by numerous lawyers, historians and other academics as ecocide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Defoliants eroded tree cover and seedling forest stock, making reforestation difficult in numerous areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Animal species diversity is sharply reduced in contrast with unsprayed areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The use of Agent Orange in Vietnam resulted in numerous legal actions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The United Nations ratified General Assembly Resolution 31/72 in 1976 and the Environmental Modification Convention in 1977.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Under the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) definition, Agent Orange is not considered a chemical weapon as it was not used to cause intentional death or harm to humans through its toxic properties.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Lawsuits have been filed on behalf of both U.S. and Vietnamese veterans and civilians seeking compensation for damages.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The active ingredient of Agent Orange was an equal mixture of two phenoxy herbicides – 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4-D) and 2,4,5-trichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4,5-T) – in iso-octyl ester form, which contained traces of the dioxin 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-*p*-dioxin (TCDD).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] TCDD was a trace, but significant, contaminant of Agent Orange (typically 2–3 ppm, ranging from 50 ppb to 50 ppm).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] TCDD is the most toxic of the dioxins and is classified as a human carcinogen by the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The fat-soluble nature of TCDD causes it to accumulate easily in the food chain, and can enter the body readily through physical contact or ingestion.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] When TCDD binds to cytoplasmic aryl hydrocarbon receptor (AhR), a transcription factor, the protein translocates to the cell nucleus, where it influences gene expression.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] According to U.S. government reports, if not bound chemically to a biological surface such as soil, leaves or grass, Agent Orange dries quickly after spraying and breaks down within hours to days when exposed to sunlight and is no longer harmful.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Several herbicides were developed as part of efforts by the United States and the United Kingdom to create herbicidal weapons for use during World War II.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] These included 2,4-D, 2,4,5-T, MCPA (2-methyl-4-chlorophenoxyacetic acid, 1414B and 1414A, recoded LN-8 and LN-32), and isopropyl phenylcarbamate (1313, recoded LN-33).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] While a graduate and post-graduate student at the University of Illinois, Galston's research and dissertation focused on finding a chemical means to make soybeans flower and fruit earlier.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] He discovered both that 2,3,5-triiodobenzoic acid (TIBA) would speed up the flowering of soybeans and that in higher concentrations it would defoliate the soybeans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] From these studies arose the concept of using aerial applications of herbicides to destroy enemy crops to disrupt their food supply.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Army ran tests of various 2,4-D and 2,4,5-T mixtures at the Bushnell Army Airfield in Florida.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] As a result, the U.S. began a full-scale production of 2,4-D and 2,4,5-T and would have used it against Japan in 1946 during Operation Downfall if the war had continued.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In the years after the war, the U.S. tested 1,100 compounds, and field trials of the more promising ones were done at British stations in India and Australia, in order to establish their effects in tropical conditions, as well as at the U.S. testing ground in Florida.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Between 1950 and 1952, trials were conducted in Tanganyika, at Kikore and Stunyansa, to test arboricides and defoliants under tropical conditions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The chemicals involved were 2,4-D, 2,4,5-T, and endothall (3,6-endoxohexahydrophthalic acid).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] During 1952–53, the unit supervised the aerial spraying of 2,4,5-T in Kenya to assess the value of defoliants in the eradication of tsetse fly.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In Malaya, the local unit of Imperial Chemical Industries researched defoliants as weed killers for rubber plantations.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Roadside ambushes by the Malayan National Liberation Army were a danger to the British Commonwealth forces during the Malayan Emergency, several trials were made to defoliate vegetation that might hide ambush sites, but hand removal was found cheaper.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] A detailed account of how the British experimented with the spraying of herbicides was written by two scientists, E.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Woodford of Agricultural Research Council's Unit of Experimental Agronomy and H.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] After the Malayan Emergency ended in 1960, the U.S. considered the British precedent in deciding that the use of defoliants was a legal tactic of warfare.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Secretary of State Dean Rusk advised President John F.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Kennedy that the British had established a precedent for warfare with herbicides in Malaya.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In mid-1961, President Ngo Dinh Diem of South Vietnam asked the United States to help defoliate the lush jungle that was providing cover to the North Vietnamese army and Viet Cong.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In August of that year, the Republic of Vietnam Air Force conducted herbicide operations with American help.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Diem's request launched a policy debate in the White House and the State and Defense Departments.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Many U.S. officials supported herbicide operations, pointing out that the British had already used herbicides and defoliants in Malaya during the 1950s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In November 1961, Kennedy authorized the start of Operation Ranch Hand, the codename for the United States Air Force's herbicide program in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The herbicide operations were formally directed by the government of South Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] As the British did in Malaya, the goal of the U.S. was to defoliate rural/forested land, depriving guerrillas of food and concealment and clearing sensitive areas such as around base perimeters and possible ambush sites along roads and canals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Huntington argued that the program was also part of a policy of forced draft urbanization, which aimed to destroy the ability of peasants to support themselves in the countryside, forcing them to flee to the U.S.-dominated cities, depriving the guerrillas of their rural support base.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange was usually sprayed from helicopters or from low-flying C-123 Provider aircraft planes, fitted with sprayers and "MC-1 Hourglass" pump systems and 1,000 U.S. gal (3,800 L; 830 imp gal) chemical tanks.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Spray runs were also conducted from trucks, boats, and backpack sprayers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The first batch of herbicides was unloaded at Tan Son Nhut Air Base in South Vietnam on January 9, 1962.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Air Force records show that at least 6,542 spraying missions took place throughout Operation Ranch Hand.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] By 1971, 12 percent of the total area of South Vietnam had been sprayed with defoliating chemicals, at an average concentration of 13 times the recommended U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Department of Agriculture application rate for domestic use.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In South Vietnam alone, an estimated 39,000 sq mi (100,000 km2) of agricultural land was ultimately destroyed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In some areas, TCDD concentrations in soil and water were hundreds of times greater than the levels considered safe by the EPA.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The campaign destroyed 7,700 sq mi (20,000 km2) of upland and mangrove forests and thousands of square kilometres of crops.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Overall, more than 20% of South Vietnam's forests were sprayed at least once over the nine years.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] 3.2% of South Vietnam's cultivated land was sprayed at least once between 1965 and 1971.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] 90% of herbicide use was directed at defoliation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. military began targeting food crops in October 1962, primarily using Agent Blue; the American public was not made aware of the crop destruction programs until 1965 (and it was then believed that crop spraying had begun that spring).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In 1965, 42% of all herbicide spraying was dedicated to food crops.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Congress were told, "crop destruction is understood to be the more important purpose ... but the emphasis is usually given to the jungle defoliation in public mention of the program." The first official acknowledgment of the programs came from the State Department in March 1966.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] When crops were destroyed, the National Liberation Front would compensate for the loss of food by confiscating more food from local villages.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Some military personnel reported being told they were destroying crops used to feed guerrillas, only to later discover, most of the destroyed food was actually produced to support the local civilian population.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Wil Verwey wrote in 1977 that ecologist Arthur H.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Westing, during a 1969 visit to the Quang Ngai province, had been told that 15 crop destruction missions had been approved in the province for 1970.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] According to Verwey, these missions would have been enough to cover 85% of crop lands in the province and would have caused famine and left hundreds of thousands of people without food or malnourished although it was unclear if all the approved missions were actually carried out.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] According to a report by the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the herbicide campaign had disrupted the food supply of more than 600,000 people by 1970.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Many experts at the time, including plant physiologist and bioethicist Arthur Galston, opposed herbicidal warfare because of concerns about the side effects to humans and the environment from indiscriminately spraying the chemical over a wide area.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] As early as 1966, resolutions were introduced to the United Nations charging that the U.S. was violating the 1925 Geneva Protocol, which regulated the use of chemical and biological weapons in international conflicts.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. defeated most of the resolutions, arguing that Agent Orange was not a chemical or a biological weapon as it was considered an herbicide and a defoliant and it was used in effort to destroy plant crops and to deprive the enemy of concealment and not meant to target human beings.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. delegation argued that a weapon, by definition, is any device used to injure, defeat, or destroy living beings, structures, or systems, and Agent Orange did not qualify under that definition.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] It also argued that if the U.S. were to be charged for using Agent Orange, then the United Kingdom and its Commonwealth nations should be charged since they also used it widely during the Malayan Emergency in the 1950s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] A study carried out by the Bionetic Research Laboratories between 1965 and 1968 found malformations in test animals caused by 2,4,5-T, a component of Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The study was later brought to the attention of the White House in October 1969.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Other studies reported similar results and the Department of Defense began to reduce the herbicide operation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] On April 15, 1970, it was announced that the use of Agent Orange was suspended.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Two brigades of the Americal Division in the summer of 1970 continued to use Agent Orange for crop destruction in violation of the suspension.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] An investigation led to disciplinary action against the brigade and division commanders because they had falsified reports to hide its use.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Defoliation and crop destruction were completely stopped by June 30, 1971.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] There are various types of cancer associated with Agent Orange, including chronic B-cell leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma, multiple myeloma, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, prostate cancer, respiratory cancer, lung cancer, and soft tissue sarcomas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Some literature claims that neither Agent Orange nor its contaminants are carcinogenic in humans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The government of Vietnam states that 4 million of its citizens were exposed to Agent Orange, and as many as 3 million have suffered illnesses because of it; these figures include their children who were exposed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The Red Cross of Vietnam estimates that up to 1 million people are disabled or have health problems due to Agent Orange contamination.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The United States government has challenged these figures as being unreliable.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Nguyen Viet Nhan, children in the areas where Agent Orange was used have been affected and have multiple health problems, including cleft palate, mental disabilities, hernias, and extra fingers and toes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In the 1970s, high levels of dioxin were found in the breast milk of South Vietnamese women, and in the blood of U.S. military personnel who had served in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The most affected zones are the mountainous area along Truong Son (Long Mountains) and the border between Vietnam and Cambodia.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The affected residents are living in substandard conditions with many genetic diseases.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In 2006, Anh Duc Ngo and colleagues of the University of Texas Health Science Center published a meta-analysis that exposed a large amount of heterogeneity (different findings) between studies, a finding consistent with a lack of consensus on the issue.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Despite this, statistical analysis of the studies they examined resulted in data that the increase in birth defects/relative risk (RR) from exposure to agent orange/dioxin "appears" to be on the order of 3 in Vietnamese-funded studies, but 1.29 in the rest of the world.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] There is data near the threshold of statistical significance suggesting Agent Orange contributes to stillbirths, cleft palate, and neural tube defects, with spina bifida being the most statistically significant defect.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The large discrepancy in RR between Vietnamese studies and those in the rest of the world has been ascribed to bias in the Vietnamese studies.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Twenty-eight of the former U.S. military bases in Vietnam, where the herbicides were stored and loaded onto airplanes, may still have high levels of dioxins in the soil, posing a health threat to the surrounding communities.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Extensive testing for dioxin contamination has been conducted at the former U.S. airbases in Da Nang, Phù Cát District and Biên Hòa.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Some of the soil and sediment on the bases have extremely high levels of dioxin, requiring remediation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The Da Nang Air Base has dioxin contamination up to 350 times higher than international recommendations for action.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The contaminated soil and sediment continue to affect the citizens of Vietnam, poisoning their food chain and causing illnesses, serious skin diseases and a variety of cancers in the lungs, larynx, and prostate.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] While in Vietnam, U.S. and Free World Military Assistance Forces soldiers were told not to worry about Agent Orange and were persuaded that the chemical was harmless.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] After returning home, Vietnam veterans from all countries that served began to suspect their ill health or the instances of their wives having miscarriages or children born with birth defects might be related to Agent Orange and the other toxic herbicides to which they had been exposed in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] By April 1993, the Department of Veterans Affairs had compensated only 486 victims, although it had received disability claims from 39,419 soldiers who had been exposed to Agent Orange while serving in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Only in 1994 did the Australian government finally admit that it was true that defoliants had been used in areas of Vietnam where Australian forces operated, and the effects of these may have been detrimental to some Vietnam veterans and their children.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] It was only in 2015 that the official Australian War Memorial accepted rewriting the official history of Australia's involvement in the Vietnam War to acknowledge that Australian soldiers were exposed to defoliants used in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] New Zealand was even slower to correct its error, with the government going as far as to deny the legitimacy of the Australian reports in a report called the "McLeod Report," published by Veterans Affairs NZ in 2001, thus infuriating New Zealand veterans and those associated with their cause.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] In 2008, the New Zealand government finally admitted that New Zealanders had been exposed to Agent Orange while serving in Vietnam, and the experience was responsible for detrimental health conditions in veterans and their children.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Amendments to the memorandum made in 2021 meant that more veterans were eligible for an ex gratia payment of NZ$40,000.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Starting in the early 1990s, the federal government directed the Institute of Medicine (IOM), renamed the National Academy of Medicine, to issue reports every 2 years on the health effects of Agent Orange and similar herbicides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] First published in 1994 and titled *Veterans and Agent Orange*, the IOM reports assess the risk of both cancer and non-cancer health effects.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Each health effect is categorized by evidence of association based on available research data.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The last update was published in 2016, entitled *Veterans and Agent Orange: Update 2014*.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The report shows sufficient evidence of an association with soft tissue sarcoma; non-Hodgkin lymphoma (NHL); Hodgkin disease; Chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL); including hairy cell leukemia and other chronic B-cell leukemias.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Limited or suggested evidence of an association was linked with respiratory cancers (lung, bronchus, trachea, larynx); prostate cancer; multiple myeloma; and bladder cancer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Numerous other cancers were determined to have inadequate or insufficient evidence of links to Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] At the request of the Veterans Administration, the Institute of Medicine evaluated whether service in these C-123 aircraft could have plausibly exposed soldiers and been detrimental to their health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Their report *Post-Vietnam Dioxin Exposure in Agent Orange-Contaminated C-123 Aircraft* confirmed it.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Publications by the United States Public Health Service have shown that Vietnam veterans, overall, have increased rates of cancer, and nerve, digestive, skin, and respiratory disorders.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention notes that in particular, there are higher rates of acute/chronic leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, throat cancer, prostate cancer, lung cancer, colon cancer, ischemic heart disease, soft tissue sarcoma, and liver cancer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Except liver cancer, these are the same conditions the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Veterans Administration has determined may be associated with exposure to Agent Orange/dioxin and are on the list of conditions eligible for compensation and treatment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Military personnel who were involved in storage, mixture and transportation (including aircraft mechanics), and actual use of the chemicals were probably among those who received the heaviest exposures.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Military members who served on Okinawa also claim to have been exposed to the chemical, but there is no verifiable evidence to corroborate these claims.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Some studies have suggested that veterans exposed to Agent Orange may be more at risk of developing prostate cancer and potentially more than twice as likely to develop higher-grade, more lethal prostate cancers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] However, a critical analysis of these studies and 35 others consistently found that there was no significant increase in prostate cancer incidence or mortality in those exposed to Agent Orange or 2,3,7,8-tetracholorodibenzo-*p*-dioxin.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] During the Vietnam War, the United States fought the North Vietnamese, and their allies, in Laos and Cambodia, including heavy bombing campaigns.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] They also sprayed large quantities of Agent Orange in each of those countries.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] One noteworthy exception, according to the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] About 17.8% or 12,000 square miles (31,000 km2; 3,100,000 ha) of the total forested area of Vietnam was sprayed during the war, which disrupted the ecological equilibrium.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The persistent nature of dioxins, erosion caused by loss of tree cover, and loss of seedling forest stock meant that reforestation was difficult (or impossible) in many areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Many defoliated forest areas were quickly invaded by aggressive pioneer species (such as bamboo and cogon grass), making forest regeneration difficult and unlikely.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Animal species diversity was also impacted; in one study a Harvard biologist found 24 species of birds and 5 species of mammals in a sprayed forest, while in two adjacent sections of unsprayed forest there were, respectively, 145 and 170 species of birds and 30 and 55 species of mammals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The environmental destruction caused by this defoliation has been described by Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme, lawyers, historians and other academics as an ecocide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Dioxins from Agent Orange have persisted in the Vietnamese environment since the war, settling in the soil and sediment and entering the food chain through animals and fish that feed in the contaminated areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The movement of dioxins through the food web has resulted in bioconcentration and biomagnification.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] The areas most heavily contaminated with dioxins are former U.S. air bases.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] American policy during the Vietnam War was to destroy crops, accepting the sociopolitical impact that that would have.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p01] Crops were deliberately sprayed with Agent Orange and areas were bulldozed clear of vegetation forcing many rural civilians to cities.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The extensive environmental damage that resulted from usage of the herbicide prompted the United Nations to pass Resolution 31/72 and ratify the Environmental Modification Convention.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Many states do not regard this as a complete ban on the use of herbicides and defoliants in warfare, but it does require case-by-case consideration.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] This exception voids any protection of any military and civilian personnel from a napalm attack or something like Agent Orange, and it has been argued that it was clearly designed to cover situations like U.S. tactics in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Since at least 1978, several lawsuits have been filed against the companies which produced Agent Orange, among them Dow Chemical, Monsanto, and Diamond Shamrock.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1978, army veteran Paul Reutershan sued Dow Chemical for $10 million, after he was diagnosed with terminal cancer that he believed was a result of Agent Orange exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] After Reutershan died in December 1978, his attorneys added additional plaintiffs and refiled the lawsuit as a class action.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] That lawsuit would eventually represent thousands of veterans, and was considered one of the largest and most complex lawsuits ever brought in the US at that time.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Attorney Hy Mayerson was an early pioneer in Agent Orange litigation, working with environmental attorney Victor Yannacone in 1980 on the first class-action suits against wartime manufacturers of Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The corporate defendants sought to escape culpability by blaming everything on the U.S. government.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Hartz, as their principal client, filed the first U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange class-action lawsuit in Pennsylvania, for the injuries military personnel in Vietnam suffered through exposure to toxic dioxins in the defoliant.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Attorney Mayerson co-wrote the brief that certified the Agent Orange Product Liability action as a class action, the largest ever filed as of its filing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The firm also located and supplied critical research to the veterans' lead expert, Dr.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The chemical companies involved denied that there was a link between Agent Orange and the veterans' medical problems.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] However, on May 7, 1984, seven chemical companies settled the class-action suit out of court just hours before jury selection was to begin.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The companies agreed to pay $180 million as compensation if the veterans dropped all claims against them.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Slightly over 45% of the sum was ordered to be paid by Monsanto alone.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Many veterans who were victims of Agent Orange exposure were outraged the case had been settled instead of going to court and felt they had been betrayed by the lawyers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] "Fairness Hearings" were held in five major American cities, where veterans and their families discussed their reactions to the settlement and condemned the actions of the lawyers and courts, demanding the case be heard before a jury of their peers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Weinstein refused the appeals, claiming the settlement was "fair and just".
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] By 1989, the veterans' fears were confirmed when it was decided how the money from the settlement would be paid out.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A totally disabled Vietnam veteran would receive a maximum of $12,000 spread out over the course of 10 years.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Furthermore, by accepting the settlement payments, disabled veterans would become ineligible for many state benefits that provided far more monetary support than the settlement, such as food stamps, public assistance, and government pensions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A widow of a Vietnam veteran who died of Agent Orange exposure would receive $3,700.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On 22 August 2024, the Court of Appeal of Paris dismissed an appeal filed by Tran To Nga against 14 US corporations that supplied Agent Orange for the US army during the war in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The lawyers said that Nga will take her case to France's highest appeals court.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Only military veterans from the United States and its allies in the war have won compensation so far.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Some of the agrochemical companies in the U.S. have compensated U.S. veterans, but not to Vietnamese victims.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1980, New Jersey created the New Jersey Agent Orange Commission, the first state commission created to study its effects.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The commission's research project in association with Rutgers University was called "The Pointman Project".
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] It was disbanded by Governor Christine Todd Whitman in 1996.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] During the first phase of the project, commission researchers devised ways to determine trace dioxin levels in blood.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Before this, such levels could only be found in the adipose (fat) tissue.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The project studied dioxin (TCDD) levels in blood as well as in adipose tissue in a small group of Vietnam veterans who had been exposed to Agent Orange and compared them to those of a matched control group; the levels were found to be higher in the exposed group.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The second phase of the project continued to examine and compare dioxin levels in various groups of Vietnam veterans, including Soldiers, Marines, and Brownwater Naval personnel.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1991, Congress enacted the Agent Orange Act, giving the Department of Veterans Affairs the authority to declare certain conditions "presumptive" to exposure to Agent Orange/dioxin, making these veterans who served in Vietnam eligible to receive treatment and compensation for these conditions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The authority for the National Academy of Sciences reviews and addition of any new diseases to the presumptive list by the VA expired in 2015 under the sunset clause of the Agent Orange Act of 1991.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Through this process, the list of 'presumptive' conditions has grown since 1991, and currently the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] This list now includes B cell leukemias, such as hairy cell leukemia, Parkinson's disease and ischemic heart disease, these last three having been added on August 31, 2010.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Several highly placed individuals in government are voicing concerns about whether some of the diseases on the list should, in fact, actually have been included.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2011, an appraisal of the 20-year long *Air Force Health Study* that began in 1982 indicates that the results of the AFHS as they pertain to Agent Orange, do not provide evidence of disease in the Operation Ranch Hand veterans caused by "their elevated levels of exposure to Agent Orange".
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The VA initially denied the applications of post-Vietnam C-123 aircrew veterans because, as veterans without "boots on the ground" service in Vietnam, they were not covered under VA's interpretation of "exposed".
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In June 2015, the Secretary of Veterans Affairs issued an Interim final rule providing presumptive service connection for post-Vietnam C-123 aircrews, maintenance staff and aeromedical evacuation crews.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The VA now provides medical care and disability compensation for the recognized list of Agent Orange illnesses.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2002, Vietnam and the U.S. held a joint conference on Human Health and Environmental Impacts of Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences (NIEHS) began scientific exchanges between the U.S. and Vietnam, and began discussions for a joint research project on the human health impacts of Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] These negotiations broke down in 2005, when neither side could agree on the research protocol, and the research project was canceled.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] More progress has been made on the environmental front.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2005, the first U.S.-Vietnam workshop on remediation of dioxin was held.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Starting in 2005, the EPA began to work with the Vietnamese government to measure the level of dioxin at the Da Nang Air Base.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Also in 2005, the Joint Advisory Committee on Agent Orange, made up of representatives of Vietnamese and U.S. government agencies, was established.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The committee has been meeting yearly to explore areas of scientific cooperation, technical assistance and environmental remediation of dioxin.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A breakthrough in the diplomatic stalemate on this issue occurred as a result of United States President George W.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Bush's state visit to Vietnam in November 2006.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The appropriation was renewed in the fiscal year 2009 and again in FY 2010.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] An additional $12 million was appropriated in the fiscal year 2010 in the Supplemental Appropriations Act and a total of $18.5 million appropriated for fiscal year 2011.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton stated during a visit to Hanoi in October 2010 that the U.S. government would begin work on the clean-up of dioxin contamination at the Da Nang Airbase.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In June 2011, a ceremony was held at Da Nang airport to mark the start of U.S.-funded decontamination of dioxin hotspots in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Thirty-two million dollars has so far been allocated by the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A $43 million project began in the summer of 2012, as Vietnam and the U.S. forge closer ties to boost trade and counter China's rising influence in the disputed South China Sea.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Dow Chemical and Monsanto were the two largest producers of Agent Orange for the U.S. military and were named in the suit, along with the dozens of other companies (Diamond Shamrock, Uniroyal, Thompson Chemicals, Hercules, etc.).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Weinstein of the Eastern District – who had presided over the 1984 U.S. veterans class-action lawsuit – dismissed the lawsuit, ruling there was no legal basis for the plaintiffs' claims.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] He concluded Agent Orange was not considered a poison under international humanitarian law at the time of its use by the U.S.; the U.S. was not prohibited from using it as a herbicide; and the companies that produced the substance were not liable for the method of its use by the government.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The U.S. government was also not a party in the lawsuit because of sovereign immunity, and the court ruled the chemical companies, as contractors of the U.S. government, shared the same immunity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The case was appealed and heard by the Second Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan on June 18, 2007.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Three judges on the court upheld Weinstein's ruling to dismiss the case.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] They ruled that, though the herbicides contained a dioxin (a known poison), they were not intended to be used as a poison on humans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Therefore, they were not considered a chemical weapon and thus not a violation of international law.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A further review of the case by the entire panel of judges of the Court of Appeals also confirmed this decision.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The lawyers for the Vietnamese filed a petition to the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On March 2, 2009, the Supreme Court denied certiorari and declined to reconsider the ruling of the Court of Appeals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] To assist those who have been affected by Agent Orange/dioxin, the Vietnamese have established "peace villages", which each host between 50 and 100 victims, giving them medical and psychological help.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] As of 2006, there were 11 such villages, thus granting some social protection to fewer than a thousand victims.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] U.S. veterans of the war in Vietnam and individuals who are aware and sympathetic to the impacts of Agent Orange have supported these programs in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] An international group of veterans from the U.S. and its allies during the Vietnam War working with their former enemy—veterans from the Vietnam Veterans Association—established the Vietnam Friendship Village outside of Hanoi.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The center provides medical care, rehabilitation and vocational training for children and veterans from Vietnam who have been affected by Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1998, The Vietnam Red Cross established the Vietnam Agent Orange Victims Fund to provide direct assistance to families throughout Vietnam that have been affected.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2004, the Vietnam Association of Victims of Agent Orange (VAVA) was formed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In addition to filing the lawsuit against the chemical companies, VAVA provides medical care, rehabilitation services and financial assistance to those injured by Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The Vietnamese government provides small monthly stipends to more than 200,000 Vietnamese people believed to be affected by the herbicides; this totaled $40.8 million in 2008.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On June 16, 2010, members of the U.S.-Vietnam Dialogue Group on Agent Orange/Dioxin unveiled a comprehensive 10-year Declaration and Plan of Action to address the toxic legacy of Agent Orange and other herbicides in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On September 16, 2010, Senator Patrick Leahy acknowledged the work of the Dialogue Group by releasing a statement on the floor of the United States Senate.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The statement urges the U.S. government to take the Plan of Action's recommendations into account in developing a multi-year plan of activities to address the Agent Orange/dioxin legacy.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2008, Australian researcher Jean Williams claimed that cancer rates in Innisfail, Queensland, were 10 times higher than the state average because of secret testing of Agent Orange by the Australian military scientists during the Vietnam War.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Williams, who had won the Order of Australia medal for her research on the effects of chemicals on U.S. war veterans, based her allegations on Australian government reports found in the Australian War Memorial's archives.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A former soldier, Ted Bosworth, backed up the claims, saying that he had been involved in the secret testing.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Neither Williams nor Bosworth has produced verifiable evidence to support their claims.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The Queensland health department determined that cancer rates in Innisfail were no higher than those in other parts of the state.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The U.S. military, with the permission of the Canadian government, tested herbicides, including Agent Orange, in the forests near Canadian Forces Base Gagetown in New Brunswick.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2007, the government of Canada offered a one-time ex gratia payment of $20,000 as compensation for Agent Orange exposure at CFB Gagetown.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On July 12, 2005, Merchant Law Group, on behalf of over 1,100 Canadian veterans and civilians who were living in and around CFB Gagetown, filed a lawsuit to pursue class action litigation concerning Agent Orange and Agent Purple with the Federal Court of Canada.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On August 4, 2009, the case was rejected by the court, citing lack of evidence.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2007, the Canadian government announced that a research and fact-finding program initiated in 2005 had found the base was safe.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On February 17, 2011, the *Toronto Star* revealed that Agent Orange had been employed to clear extensive plots of Crown land in Northern Ontario.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] An analysis of chemicals present in the island's soil, together with resolutions passed by Guam's legislature, suggest that Agent Orange was among the herbicides routinely used on and around Andersen Air Force Base and Naval Air Station Agana.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Despite the evidence, the Department of Defense continues to deny that Agent Orange was stored or used on Guam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange was used in South Korea in the late 1960s and in 1999, about 20,000 South Koreans filed two separated lawsuits against U.S. companies, seeking more than $5 billion in damages.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] After losing a decision in 2002, they filed an appeal.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In January 2006, the South Korean Appeals Court ordered Dow Chemical and Monsanto to pay $62 million in compensation to about 6,800 people.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The ruling acknowledged that "the defendants failed to ensure safety as the defoliants manufactured by the defendants had higher levels of dioxins than standard", and, quoting the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] National Academy of Science report, declared that there was a "causal relationship" between Agent Orange and a range of diseases, including several cancers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The judges failed to acknowledge "the relationship between the chemical and peripheral neuropathy, the disease most widespread among Agent Orange victims".
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2011, the United States local press KPHO-TV in Phoenix, Arizona, alleged that in 1978 that the United States Army had buried 250 55-gallon drums (13,750 U.S. gal (52,000 L; 11,450 imp gal)) of Agent Orange in Camp Carroll, the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Army base located in Gyeongsangbuk-do, South Korea.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Currently, veterans who provide evidence meeting VA requirements for service in Vietnam and who can medically establish that anytime after this 'presumptive exposure' they developed any medical problems on the list of presumptive diseases, may receive compensation from the VA.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Certain veterans who served in South Korea and can prove they were assigned to certain specified areas around the Korean Demilitarized Zone, during a specific time frame, are afforded similar presumption.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] What is fact is that from 1962 until 1987, 2,4,5T herbicide was manufactured at the Ivon Watkins-Dow plant for domestic use in New Zealand.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] It was widely used by farmers and in New Zealand agriculture as a weed killer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] This fact was the basis of a 2005 New Zealand Media story that claimed that the herbicide had been allegedly exported to U.S. military bases in South East Asia.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] However the claim was not proven, a fact which the Media did not subsequently report.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] There have been continuing claims, as yet unproven, that the suburb of Paritutu has also been polluted.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] However, the agriscience company Corteva (which split from DowDupont in 2019) agreed to clean up the Paritutu site in September 2022.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Herbicide persistence studies of Agents Orange and White were conducted in the Philippines.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Air Force operation to remove Herbicide Orange from Vietnam in 1972 was named Operation Pacer IVY, while the operation to destroy the Agent Orange stored at Johnston Atoll in 1977 was named Operation Pacer HO.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Operation Pacer IVY collected Agent Orange in South Vietnam and removed it in 1972 aboard the ship MV Transpacific for storage on Johnston Atoll.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The EPA reports that 6,800,000 L (1,800,000 U.S. gal) of Herbicide Orange was stored at Johnston Island in the Pacific and 1,800,000 L (480,000 U.S. gal) at Gulfport, Mississippi.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Research and studies were initiated to find a safe method to destroy the materials, and it was discovered that they could be incinerated safely under special conditions of temperature and dwell time.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] However, these herbicides were expensive, and the Air Force wanted to resell its surplus instead of dumping it at sea.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Among many methods tested, a possibility of salvaging the herbicides by reprocessing and filtering out the TCDD contaminant with carbonized (charcoaled) coconut fibers.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] This concept was then tested in 1976, and a pilot plant constructed at Gulfport.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] As of 2004, some records of the storage and disposition of Agent Orange at Johnston Atoll have been associated with the historical records of Operation Red Hat.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] There have been dozens of reports in the press about the use and/or storage of military-formulated herbicides on Okinawa that are based upon statements by former U.S. service members that had been stationed on the island, photographs, government records, and unearthed storage barrels.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Department of Defense has denied these allegations with statements by military officials and spokespersons, as well as a January 2013 report authored by Dr.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Alvin Young that was released in April 2013.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In particular, the 2013 report rebuts articles written by journalist Jon Mitchell as well as a statement from "An Ecological Assessment of Johnston Atoll" a 2003 publication produced by the United States Army Chemical Materials Agency that states, "in 1972, the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange was tested by the United States in Thailand during the Vietnam War.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1999, buried drums were uncovered and confirmed to be Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Workers who uncovered the drums fell ill while upgrading the airport near Hua Hin District, 100 km south of Bangkok.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Vietnam-era veterans whose service involved duty on or near the perimeters of military bases in Thailand anytime between February 28, 1961, and May 7, 1975, may have been exposed to herbicides and may qualify for VA benefits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A declassified Department of Defense report written in 1973, suggests that there was a significant use of herbicides on the fenced-in perimeters of military bases in Thailand to remove foliage that provided cover for enemy forces.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2013, the VA determined that herbicides used on the Thailand base perimeters may have been tactical and procured from Vietnam, or a strong, commercial type resembling tactical herbicides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1971, the C-123 aircraft used for spraying Agent Orange were returned to the United States and assigned various East Coast USAF Reserve squadrons, and then employed in traditional airlift missions between 1972 and 1982.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1994, testing by the Air Force identified some former spray aircraft as "heavily contaminated" with dioxin residue.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Inquiries by aircrew veterans in 2011 brought a decision by the U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Department of Veterans Affairs opining that not enough dioxin residue remained to injure these post-Vietnam War veterans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Center For Disease Control's Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry challenged this with their finding that former spray aircraft were indeed contaminated and the aircrews exposed to harmful levels of dioxin.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In response to veterans' concerns, the VA in February 2014 referred the C-123 issue to the Institute of Medicine for a special study, with results released on January 9, 2015.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1978, the EPA suspended spraying of Agent Orange in national forests.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange was sprayed on thousands of acres of brush in the Tennessee Valley for 15 years before scientists discovered the herbicide was dangerous.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Monroe County, Tennessee, is one of the locations known to have been sprayed according to the Tennessee Valley Authority.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Forty-four remote acres were sprayed with Agent Orange along power lines throughout the National Forest.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 1983, New Jersey declared a Passaic River production site to be a state of emergency.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The dioxin pollution in the Passaic River dates back to the Vietnam era, when Diamond Alkali manufactured it in a factory along the river.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The tidal river carried dioxin upstream and down, contaminating a 17 mi (27 km) stretch of riverbed in one of New Jersey's most populous areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] A December 2006 Department of Defense report listed Agent Orange testing, storage, and disposal sites at 32 locations throughout the United States, Canada, Thailand, Puerto Rico, Korea, and in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The Veteran Administration has also acknowledged that Agent Orange was used domestically by U.S. forces in test sites throughout the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Eglin Air Force Base in Florida was one of the primary testing sites throughout the 1960s.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In February 2012, Monsanto agreed to settle a case covering dioxin contamination around a plant in Nitro, West Virginia, that had manufactured Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Monsanto agreed to pay up to $9 million for cleanup of affected homes, $84 million for medical monitoring of people affected, and the community's legal fees.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] On 9 August 2012, the United States and Vietnam began a cooperative cleaning up of the toxic chemical on part of Da Nang International Airport, marking the first time the U.S. government has been involved in cleaning up Agent Orange in Vietnam.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Danang was the primary storage site of the chemical.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Two other cleanup sites the United States and Vietnam are looking at is Biên Hòa, in the southern province of Đồng Nai is a hotspot for dioxin and so is Phù Cát airport in the central province of Bình Định, says U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] According to the Vietnamese newspaper *Nhân Dân*, the U.S. government provided $41 million to the project.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The Naval Construction Battalion Center at Gulfport, Mississippi was the largest storage site in the United States for Agent Orange.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] It was about 30 acres (12 ha) in size and was still being cleaned up in 2013.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] In 2016, the EPA laid out its plan for cleaning up an 8 mi (13 km) stretch of the Passaic River in New Jersey, with an estimated cost of $1.4 billion.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] The contaminants reached to Newark Bay and other waterways, according to the EPA, which has designated the area a Superfund site.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agent-orange-p02] Since destruction of the dioxin requires high temperatures over 1,000 °C (1,830 °F), the destruction process is energy intensive.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Management practices, or ignorance of them, play a crucial role in the amount and impact of these pollutants.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Management techniques range from animal management and housing to the spread of pesticides and fertilizers in global agricultural practices, which can have major environmental impacts.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Bad management practices include poorly managed animal feeding operations, overgrazing, plowing, fertilizer, and improper, excessive, or badly timed use of pesticides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Pollutants from agriculture greatly affect water quality and can be found in lakes, rivers, wetlands, estuaries, and groundwater.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Pollutants from farming include sediments, nutrients, pathogens, pesticides, metals, and salts.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Animal agriculture has an outsized impact on pollutants that enter the environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Bacteria and pathogens in manure can make their way into streams and groundwater if grazing, storing manure in lagoons and applying manure to fields is not properly managed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Air pollution caused by agriculture through land use changes and animal agriculture practices have an outsized impact on climate change.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Addressing these concerns was a central part of the IPCC Special Report on Climate Change and Land as well as in the 2024 UNEP Actions on Air Quality report.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Mitigation of agricultural pollution is a key component in the development of a sustainable food system.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It has been conceded that in the absence of pest control measures, crop losses before harvesting would typically amount to 40 percent.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Pesticide persistence is nonetheless a major issue.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] For example 2,4-D and atrazine have with lifetimes up to 20 years.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] DDT, aldrin, dieldrin, endrin, heptachlor, and toxaphene are also long-lived.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The persistence of pesticides and herbicides persist depends on the compound's unique chemistry.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Pesticides can also accumulate in animals that eat contaminated pests and soil organisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The primary danger associated with pesticide application lies in its impact on non-target organisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In principle, biopesticides, derived from natural sources, could reduce overall agricultural pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Furthermore, biopesticides often suffer the same negative impacts as synthetic pesticides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In the United States, biopesticides are subject to fewer environmental regulations.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Many biopesticides are permitted under the National Organic Program, United States Department of Agriculture, standards for organic crop production.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Pesticide leaching occurs when aqueous solutions of pesticides migrate to off-target sites.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Leaching is a major source of groundwater pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Leaching is affected by the soil, the pesticide, and rainfall and irrigation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Leaching is more problematic with water-soluble pesticides and when the soil tends to be sandy in texture; if excessive watering occurs just after pesticide application; if the adsorption ability of the pesticide to the soil is low.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In addition to treated fields, Leaching may also originate from pesticide mixing areas, pesticide application machinery washing sites, or disposal areas.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] While providing crops with nutrients to increase crop yields, fertilizers can pose risks to human and ecological health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Most common nitrogen sources are NO3− (nitrate) and NH4+ (ammonium).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Although leading to increased crop yield, nitrogen fertilizers can also negatively affect groundwater and surface waters, pollute the atmosphere, and degrade soil health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Not all nutrient applied through fertilizer are taken up by the crops, and the remainder accumulates in the soil or is lost as runoff.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Nitrate fertilizers are much more likely to be lost to the soil profile through runoff because of its high solubility and like charges between the molecule and negatively charged clay particles.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] High application rates of nitrogen-containing fertilizers combined with the high water-solubility of nitrate leads to increased runoff into surface water as well as leaching into groundwater, thereby causing groundwater pollution.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Nitrate levels above 10 mg/L (10 ppm) in groundwater can cause "blue baby syndrome" (acquired methemoglobinemia) in infants and possibly thyroid disease and various types of cancer.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] They allow nitrogen to flow between the atmosphere, which is around 78% nitrogen) and the biosphere.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Other significant processes in the nitrogen cycle are nitrification and ammonification which convert ammonium to nitrate or nitrite and organic matter to ammonia respectively.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Because these processes keep nitrogen concentrations relatively stable in most ecosystems, a large influx of nitrogen from agricultural runoff can cause serious disruption.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A common result of this in aquatic ecosystems is eutrophication, which in turn creates hypoxic and anoxic conditions – both of which are deadly and/or damaging to many species..
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Beyond eutrophication, nitrogen pollution—specifically in the form of nitrite (NO2−)—acts as a significant driver of species turnover in riverine ecosystems.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Research indicates that aquatic invertebrates exhibit a wide range of sensitivities; while molluscs are relatively tolerant, aquatic insects such as mayflies and stoneflies are highly sensitive to nitrite exposure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In groups like amphipods, sensitivity varies by habitat, with upstream species (e.g., *Gammarus fossarum*) being more vulnerable than midstream or invasive downstream species (e.g., *Gammarus roeselii*).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This differential sensitivity can lead to the replacement of native sensitive taxa with more tolerant ones, potentially altering ecosystem functions like leaf litter decomposition and nutrient cycling.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Nitrogen fertilization can also release NH3 gases into the atmosphere which can then be converted into NOx compounds.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A greater amount of NOx compounds in the atmosphere can result in the acidification of aquatic ecosystems and cause various respiratory issues in humans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Fertilization can also release N2O which is a greenhouse gas and can facilitate the destruction of ozone (O3) in the stratosphere.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Soils that receive nitrogen fertilizers can also be damaged.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] An increase in plant available nitrogen will increase a crop's net primary production, and eventually, soil microbial activity will increase as a result of the larger inputs of nitrogen from fertilizers and carbon compounds through decomposed biomass.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Excess nitrogen can disrupt mutualisms; for example, in the legumes-rhizobia resource mutualism nitrogen deposition results in the evolution of less-cooperative rhizobia.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Because of the increase in decomposition in the soil, its organic matter content will be depleted which results in lower overall soil health.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The most common form of phosphorus fertilizer is phosphate (PO43-).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It is applied as synthetic phosphate salts as well as manure and compost.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Most agricultural crops only require a small amount of phosphorus, as such, the amount of phosphorus supplied is often excessive.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Excess phosphorus typically enters surface waters.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Phosphorus is largest contributor to eutrophication, especially in freshwaters.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In addition to depleting oxygen levels in surface waters, algae and cyanobacteria blooms can produce cyanotoxins which are harmful to human and animal health as well as many aquatic organisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Cadmium is common in phosphorus-containing fertilizers varies considerably and can be problematic.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The phosphate rock used in their manufacture can contain as much as 188 mg/kg cadmium (examples are deposits on Nauru and the Christmas islands).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Continuous use of high-cadmium fertilizer can contaminate soil and plants.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Limits to the cadmium content of phosphate fertilizers has been considered by the European Commission.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Producers of phosphorus-containing fertilizers now select phosphate rock based on the cadmium content.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Phosphate rocks can also contain high levels of fluoride.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Consequently, the widespread use of phosphate fertilizers has increased soil fluoride concentrations.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It has been found that food contamination from fertilizer is of little concern as plants accumulate little fluoride from the soil; of greater concern is the possibility of fluoride toxicity to livestock that ingest contaminated soils.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Also of possible concern are the effects of fluoride on soil microorganisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Farm machinery and equipment emitting substantial quantities of harmful gases, and operation of the machinery can result in other chemical contamination, such as oil spills, hydraulic fluid leakage, and tire particulates.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Other equipment and materials used in agriculture can introduce pollutants into the soil, and subsequently the environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] For example, the widespread use of plastic sheeting for greenhouses, plastic storage for applications like animal feed and seed bags and sillage, and plastic mulch means that both microplastic and macroplastic are increasingly introduced into farmed landscapes.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A 2021 study by FAO of plastic waste in agriculture, found an estimated 10 million tons of plastic waste produced each year.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Collection of agricultural plastics is very low globally, with much of never getting collected.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Agriculture contributes greatly to soil erosion and sediment deposition through intensive management or inefficient land cover.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It is estimated that agricultural land degradation is leading to an irreversible decline in fertility on about 6 million ha of fertile land each year.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The accumulation of sediments (i.e. sedimentation) in runoff water affects water quality in various ways.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Sedimentation can decrease the transport capacity of ditches, streams, rivers, and navigation channels.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It can also limit the amount of light penetrating the water, which affects aquatic biota.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The resulting turbidity from sedimentation can interfere with feeding habits of fishes, affecting population dynamics.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Sedimentation also affects the transport and accumulation of pollutants, including phosphorus and various pesticides.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Natural soil biogeochemical processes result in the emission of various greenhouse gases, including nitrous oxide.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Agricultural management practices can affect emission levels.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] For example, tillage levels have also been shown to affect nitrous oxide emissions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] From an environmental perspective, fertilizing, overproduction and the use of pesticides in conventional farming has caused, and is causing, enormous damage worldwide to local ecosystems, soil health, biodiversity, groundwater and drinking water supplies, and sometimes farmers' health and fertility.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Organic farming typically reduces some environmental impact relative to conventional farming, but the scale of reduction can be difficult to quantify and varies depending on farming methods.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In some cases, reducing food waste and dietary changes might provide greater benefits.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A 2020 study at the Technical University of Munich found that the greenhouse gas emissions of organically farmed plant-based food were lower than conventionally farmed plant-based food.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The greenhouse gas costs of organically produced meat were approximately the same as non-organically produced meat.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] However, the same paper noted that a shift from conventional to organic practices would likely be beneficial for long-term efficiency and ecosystem services, and probably improve soil over time.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Recent research has suggested that the usage of organic fertilizers and cover crops can enhance soil organic carbon, nutrient cycling, and biodiversity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Simultaneously, it could also reduce greenhouse gas emissions when it is managed effectively.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Conservation agriculture relies on principles of minimal soil disturbance, the use of mulch and/or cover crops as soil cover, and crop species diversification.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It enables the reduction of fertilizers, which in turn reduces ammonia emissions and greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] It also stabilizes soil, which slows down the release of carbon into the atmosphere.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Manures and biosolids, although having value as fertilizers, they may also contain contaminants, including pharmaceuticals and personal care products (PPCPs).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A wide variety and vast quantity of PPCPs consumed by animals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) predicted that 18% of anthropogenic greenhouse gases come directly or indirectly from the world's livestock.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This report also suggested that the emissions from livestock were greater than that of the transportation sector.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] While livestock do currently play a role in producing greenhouse gas emissions, the estimates have been argued to be a misrepresentation.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] While the FAO used a life-cycle assessment of animal agriculture (i.e. all aspects including emissions from growing crops for feed, transportation to slaughter, etc.), they did not apply the same assessment for the transportation sector.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Alternate sources claim that FAO estimates are too low, stating that the global livestock industry could be responsible for up to 51% of emitted atmospheric greenhouse gasses rather than 18%.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Critics say the difference in estimates come from the FAO's use of outdated data.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Regardless, if the FAO's report of 18% is accurate, that still makes livestock the second-largest greenhouse-gas-polluter.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A PNAS model showed that even if animals were completely removed from U.S. agriculture and diets, U.S.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] GHG emissions would be decreased by 2.6% only (or 28% of agricultural GHG emissions).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This is because of the need to replace animal manures by fertilizers and to replace also other animal coproducts, and because livestock now use human-inedible food and fiber processing byproducts.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Moreover, people would suffer from a greater number of deficiencies in essential nutrients although they would get a greater excess of energy, possibly leading to greater obesity.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The increasing globalization of agriculture has resulted in the accidental transport of pests, weeds, and diseases to novel ranges.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] If they establish, they become an invasive species that can impact populations of native species and threaten agricultural production.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] For example, the transport of bumblebees reared in Europe and shipped to the United States and/or Canada for use as commercial pollinators has led to the introduction of an Old World parasite to the New World.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This introduction may play a role in recent native bumble bee declines in North America.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Agriculturally introduced species can also hybridize with native species resulting in a decline in genetic biodiversity and threaten agricultural production.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Habitat disturbance associated with farming practices themselves can also facilitate the establishment of these introduced organisms.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Contaminated machinery, livestock and fodder, and contaminated crop or pasture seed can also lead to the spread of weeds.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Quarantines (see biosecurity) are one way in which prevention of the spread of invasive species can be regulated at the policy level.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A quarantine is a legal instrument that restricts the movement of infested material from areas where an invasive species is present to areas in which it is absent.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The World Trade Organization has international regulations concerning the quarantine of pests and diseases under the Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Individual countries often have their own quarantine regulations.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In the United States, for example, the United States Department of Agriculture/Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (USDA/APHIS) administers domestic (within the United States) and foreign (importations from outside the United States) quarantines.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] These quarantines are enforced by inspectors at state borders and ports of entry.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The use of biological pest control agents, or using predators, parasitoids, parasites, and pathogens to control agricultural pests, has the potential to reduce agricultural pollution associated with other pest control techniques, such as pesticide use.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The merits of introducing non-native biocontrol agents have been widely debated, however.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Once released, the introduction of a biocontrol agent can be irreversible.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Potential ecological issues could include the dispersal from agricultural habitats into natural environments, and host-switching or adapting to utilize a native species.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In addition, predicting the interaction outcomes in complex ecosystems and potential ecological impacts prior to release can be difficult.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] One example of a biocontrol program that resulted in ecological damage occurred in North America, where a parasitoid of butterflies was introduced to control gypsy moth and browntail moth.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This parasitoid is capable of utilizing many butterfly host species, and likely resulted in the decline and extirpation of several native silk moth species.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In order to prevent agricultural pollution, quarantine and extensive research on the organism's potential efficacy and ecological impacts are required prior to introduction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] If approved, attempts are made to colonize and disperse the biocontrol agent in appropriate agricultural settings.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Continual evaluations on their efficacy are conducted.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] GMO crops can, however, result in genetic contamination of native plant species through hybridization.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This could lead to increased weediness of the plant or the extinction of the native species.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In addition, the transgenic plant itself may become a weed if the modification improves its fitness in a given environment.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] There are also concerns that non-target organisms, such as pollinators and natural enemies, could be poisoned by accidental ingestion of Bt-producing plants.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] A recent study testing the effects of Bt corn pollen dusting nearby milkweed plants on larval feeding of the monarch butterfly found that the threat to populations of the monarch was low.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The use of GMO crop plants engineered for herbicide resistance can also indirectly increase the amount of agricultural pollution associated with herbicide use.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] For example, the increased use of herbicide in herbicide-resistant corn fields in the mid-western United States is decreasing the amount of milkweeds available for monarch butterfly larvae.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Regulation of the release of genetic modified organisms vary based on the type of organism and the country concerned.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] While there may be some concerns regarding the use of GM products, it may also be the solution to some of the existing animal agriculture pollution issues.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] One of the main sources of pollution, particularly vitamin and mineral drift in soils, comes from a lack of digestive efficiency in animals.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] By improving digestive efficiency, it is possible to minimize both the cost of animal production and the environmental damage.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] One successful example of this technology and its potential application is the Enviropig.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The Enviropig is a genetically modified Yorkshire pig that expresses phytase in its saliva.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Grains, such as corn and wheat, have phosphorus that is bound in a naturally indigestible form known as phytic acid.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Phosphorus, an essential nutrient for pigs, is then added to the diet, since it can not be broken down in the pigs digestive tract.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] As a result, nearly all of the phosphorus naturally found in the grain is wasted in the feces, and can contribute to elevated levels in the soil.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Phytase is an enzyme that is able to break down the otherwise indigestible phytic acid, making it available to the pig.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The ability of the Enviropig to digest the phosphorus from the grains eliminates the waste of that natural phosphorus (20-60% reduction), while also eliminating the need to supplement the nutrient in feed.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] One of the main contributors to air, soil and water pollution is animal waste.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] According to a 2005 report by the USDA, more than 335–million tons of "dry matter" waste (the waste after water is removed) is produced annually on farms in the United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Animal feeding operations produce about 100 times more manure than the amount of human sewage sludge processed in US municipal waste water plants each year.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Diffuse source pollution from agricultural fertilizers is more difficult to trace, monitor and control.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] High nitrate concentrations are found in groundwater and may reach 50 mg/litre (the EU Directive limit).
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] In ditches and river courses, nutrient pollution from fertilizers causes eutrophication.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] This is worse in winter, after autumn ploughing has released a surge of nitrates; winter rainfall is heavier increasing runoff and leaching, and there is lower plant uptake.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] EPA suggests that one dairy farm with 2,500 cows produces as much waste as a city with around 411,000 residents.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The US National Research Council has identified odors as the most significant animal emission problem at the local level.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Different animal systems have adopted several waste management procedures to deal with the large amount of waste produced annually.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The advantages of manure treatment are a reduction in the amount of manure that needs to be transported and applied to crops, as well as reduced soil compaction.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Nutrients are reduced as well, meaning that less cropland is needed for manure to be spread upon.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Manure treatment can also reduce the risk of human health and biosecurity risks by reducing the amount of pathogens present in manure.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Undiluted animal manure or slurry is one hundred times more concentrated than domestic sewage, and can carry an intestinal parasite, *Cryptosporidium,* which is difficult to detect but can be passed to humans.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Silage liquor (from fermented wet grass) is even stronger than slurry, with a low pH and very high biological oxygen demand.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] With a low pH, silage liquor can be highly corrosive; it can attack synthetic materials, causing damage to storage equipment, and leading to accidental spillage.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] All of these advantages can be optimized by using the right manure management system on the right farm based on the resources that are available.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Composting is a solid manure management system that relies on solid manure from bedded pack pens, or the solids from a liquid manure separator.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] There are two methods of composting, active and passive.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Manure is churned periodically during active composting, whereas in passive composting it is not.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Passive composting has been found to have lower green house gas emissions due to incomplete decomposition and lower gas diffusion rates.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Manure can be mechanically separated into a solid and liquid portion for easier management.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Liquids (4–8% dry matter) can be used easily in pump systems for convenient spread over crops and the solid fraction (15–30% dry matter) can be used as stall bedding, spread on crops, composted or exported.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Anaerobic digestion is the biological treatment of liquid animal waste using bacteria in an area absent of air, which promotes the decomposition of organic solids.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Hot water is used to heat the waste in order to increase the rate of biogas production.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] The remaining liquid is nutrient rich and can be used on fields as a fertilizer and methane gas that can be burned directly on the biogas stove or in an engine generator to produce electricity and heat.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Methane is about 20 times more potent as a greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide, which has significant negative environmental effects if not controlled properly.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Anaerobic treatment of waste is the best method for controlling the odor associated with manure management.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Biological treatment lagoons also use anaerobic digestion to break down solids, but at a much slower rate.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Lagoons are kept at ambient temperatures as opposed to the heated digestion tanks.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Lagoons require large land areas and high dilution volumes to work properly, so they do not work well in many climates in the northern United States.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Lagoons also offer the benefit of reduced odor and biogas is made available for heat and electric power.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] Studies have demonstrated that GHG emissions are reduced using aerobic digestion systems.
[src:agricultural-pollution/agricultural-pollution] GHG emission reductions and credits can help compensate for the higher installation cost of cleaner aerobic technologies and facilitate producer adoption of environmentally superior technologies to replace current anaerobic lagoons.
